H. cordata growth was significantly influenced by potassium concentrations (Fig. 1
). The four growth parameters including dry weight, shoot height, root length and number showed significant differences with treatments (Table 1
). Treatment of 1.28 mM K represented the highest values of these four growth parameters, while potassium starvation (0 mM) severely inhibited the growth of H. cordata. Similarly high potassium concentrations (>1.28 mM) also caused severe reduction in these parameters. The shortest root and least root number were both found in the treatment of the highest potassium level (10.26 mM).
